<br>
Hear hear.<br>
<br>
While the detail and richness of the models and the world is incredible, for some reason the artwork doesn't grab me as much as the much more cartoony art in WoW.<br>
<br>
There are 3 problems that I can see with the EQ2 screenshots.  Problems, I might add, that are shared by the Doom3 screens I've seen in the past.<br>
<br>
1) Overuse of specular highlighting.  Way too many materials have sheen.  Everyone's clothes and armor seems to be shiny.  Even rock walls seem to be shiny.  Everyone is wearing polished, enamelled armor or silk it would seem.<br>
<br>
2) Overuse of bumpmaps/detail textures.  There's no need to try to make everything realistic.  You end up making things hyperrealistic and therefore they look &quot;wrong&quot;.   Less is more.  It's not a question of &quot;can we do this&quot; but &quot;should we do this&quot;.<br>
<br>
3) Lighting.  The lighting in the pictures is dramatic but there's something wrong.  Shadows being cast are too harsh, and lightsources fall off too fast.  Look at the picture of befallen: <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://everquest2.station.sony.com/screenshots/Befallen_Room1.jpg">everquest2.station.sony.c..._Room1.jpg</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
The room is lit by a blue-green very diffuse light, but the chair and desk are casting these razor sharp shadows.<br>
<br>
The lantern on the table is also not washing out shadows in a radius around it like it should be.<br>
<br>
<br>
In addition, the pictures of characters and monsters seem to be lit by someone using a flash camera in pitch darkness. (Go take your digital camera out in the dark, and take a picture of something with the flash to see what I mean).  The lighting is very harsh, like I have a Coleman lantern in my hand as the only source of light in the area.<br>
<br>
This is probably somewhat realistic for a dungeon with no other source of light but something about it 'sits' wrong. <br>
<br>
However it just seems strange that we get diffuse specular highlights, razor cut bump/detail maps, and razor shadows even if the room is diffusely lit.<br>
<br>
The effects may diminish somewhat when they are viewed animated.<br>
<br>
<br>
It's just interesting that while WoW is cartoony, it's visuals look cool and draw me into the world alot more than the screenshots from EQ2.  EQ2 makes me think 'neat, you have an engine that can render Max models'.<br>
<br>
I'm not sure if it's because the brain is more forgiving of obviously non-realistic (WoW) environments versus those that try (and fail) to look hyper realistic (EQ2) or what.<br>
<br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong, I'm all in favour of more detail and visual lushness in gaming worlds.  EQ2 still looks pretty; it just looks like badly lit Max renders though, instead of an immersive fantasy world.  I think that there's great risk in trying to replicate reality.  Our brains are seemingly unforgiving when we get it wrong.<br>
<br>
<br>
PS: Anyone else think that EQ2 purple spider is a refugee from the Vanu Soverignty?<br>
<br>
